President Uhuru Kenyatta on Friday ordered the suspension of sports and closure of clubs in a move aimed at checking against the spread of the coronavirus, currently in its third wave. 

Consequently, Sunday's KCB Machakos Rally, the second round of the Kenya National Rally Championship (KNRC), was cancelled at the 11th hour. 

In a statement issued on Friday, KMSF chairman Phineas Kimathi said the situation around the African Rally Championship Equator Rally will be looked into before further plans are announced. 

“The African Rally Championship Equator Rally, scheduled to be held in Kenya on April 24 and 25, 2021, will be the subject of discussion with all stakeholders next week and a decision will be taken and communicated in good time,” said Kimathi, who is also the chief executive officer of the World Rally Championship Safari Rally. 

“Let us all remain patient as we wait for the return to normalcy,’’ he appealed. 

The WRC Safari Rally will be held from June 24 to 27 principally around Naivasha. Next month’s Equator Rally will also run in Naivasha and on sections to be used for the Safari. 

It is highly likely that both competitions will take place as scheduled, but under strict Covid-19 protocols given the groundwork already done, especially for the Safari Rally that is making a return to the World Rally Championships after 19 years in the cold. 

Already, the WRC Safari Rally has appointed a Covid-19 compliance officer with regular tests scheduled for anyone working for both the Equator Rally and the Safari and safe zones created at the Service Park at Naivasha’s Kenya Wildlife Service Training Institute. 



